  "prompt": "What are some of the most common examples of an imperative sentence?",
  "response": "Imperative sentences are used to give commands, instructions, requests, or advice. They typically do not include a subject (the subject \"you\" is implied) and often begin with a verb. Here are some common examples of imperative sentences:\n\n1. **Commands:**\n   - \"Close the door.\"\n   - \"Turn off the lights.\"\n   - \"Stop talking.\"\n\n2. **Instructions:**\n   - \"Mix the ingredients thoroughly.\"\n   - \"Press the button to start.\"\n   - \"Follow the instructions carefully.\"\n\n3. **Requests:**\n   - \"Please pass the salt.\"\n   - \"Help me with this, please.\"\n   - \"Call me when you get home.\"\n\n4. **Advice:**\n   - \"Study hard for the exam.\"\n   - \"Be careful when crossing the street.\"\n   - \"Take a break if you feel tired.\"\n\n5. **Invitations or Suggestions:**\n   - \"Join us for dinner.\"\n   - \"Try the new restaurant downtown.\"\n   - \"Come to the party tonight.\"\n\n6. **Prohibitions:**\n   - \"Don't touch that.\"\n   - \"Never give up.\"\n   - \"Avoid eating too much sugar.\"\n\nThese examples illustrate how imperative sentences can be used in various contexts to direct or influence someone's actions.",
